'''Roy Perry''' (born [[12 February]] [[1943]]) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] politician.

Perry graduated from the [[University of Exeter]] with a degree in [[Government and Politics]] and was formerly a senior lecturer in [[Politics]] before entering the profession himself as a member of [[Test Valley]] [[Borough Council]] from 1979 to 1994. He was leader between 1985 and 1994. During this time, Perry contested the seat of [[Swansea West (UK Parliament constituency)|Swansea West]] for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] in the [[United Kingdom general election, 1992|1992 general election]]. He was elected a [[Member of the European Parliament]] for the [[Wight and Hampshire South (European Parliament constituency)|Wight and Hampshire South]] constituency in the [[European Parliament Election, 1994 (UK)|1994 European Parliament election]] and was re-elected under the new system of [[proportional representation]] in the [[European Parliament election, 1999 (UK)|1999 European Parliament election]].

In December [[2002]], Perry was placed sixth on the Conservative list for the 2004 elections.  Four Conservative MEPs were elected in the region so Perry was not.   

Since the [[European Parliament Election, 2004 (UK)|2004 European Parliament election]], Perry has concentrated on his roles as Director of the [[Trident Trust]], Trustee of the [[Hampshire Museums Service]], and Director of the [[Isle of Wight Partnership]].

Perry is married with two daughters.

